text: Really starting to get sick of these cheap money grabbing movies. Like Jesus Christ how many times can you tell you same fucking story!?! And I know that a boatload of people out there that are willing to come to this movies defense, arguing that you can't judge an entire movie based on a one minute trailer. Well let me ask you this, was Oz the Great and Powerful a good movie? No. Was the Alice in Wonderland reboot a good movie? No. Will Maleficent be a good movie? Probably not. When Disney allows itself to expand on new stories and adventures to tell it's avid fan-base instead of recycling the same CGI garbage over and over again they are able to entertain, dazzle, and take viewers breath away. It's really disappoints me to see Disney continue to sell out like this by making cheap, live-action garbage just to fill seats, and if it doesn't end soon, then the future of live-action Disney films foresees a weary existence. Please Disney, do something new.Â

text: Official Movie Description:Â  The story of Cinderella follows the fortunes of young Ella whose merchant father remarries following the tragic death of her mother. Keen to support her loving father, Ella welcomes her new stepmother Lady Tremaine and her daughters Anastasia and Drizella into the family home. But, when Ella's father suddenly and unexpectedly passes away, she finds herself at the mercy of a jealous and cruel new family. Finally relegated to nothing more than a servant girl covered in ashes, and spitefully renamed Cinderella, Ella could easily begin to lose hope. Yet, despite the cruelty inflicted upon her, Ella is determined to honor her mother's dying words and to "have courage and be kind." She will not give in to despair nor despise those who abuse her. And then there is the dashing stranger she meets in the woods. Unaware that he is really a prince, not merely an employee at the Palace, Ella finally feels she has met a kindred soul. It appears as if her fortunes may be about to change when the Palace sends out an open invitation for all maidens to attend a ball, raising Ella's hopes of once again encountering the charming "Kit." Alas, her stepmother forbids her to attend and callously rips apart her dress. But, as in all good fairy tales, help is at hand as a kindly beggar woman steps forward and, armed with a pumpkin and a few mice, changes Cinderella's life forever.

text: NEVER BEFORE TOLD STORY. One day Cinderella scavenged the alley and heard a Town Crier announced of a rich man in search for a wife. Ever since the announcement, poor Cinderella wasn't really just cleaning the house or baking all those breads. She collected glass bottles, secretly melted them and poured it into shoes molds in the basement. On the night of the ball, Cinderella was getting late. She cracked open the shoes molds and discovered that each shoe had a stem created from the pour hole. She didn't have time to saw it off so she wore them to the ball. Well the rest is history and the birth of high heels continue on to this day.

Yes, it's just a shoe, but look at the facets on it and butterfly. It's not just a glass slipper anymore, and obviously the heel is high, but did you expect Cinderella to wear flats or kitten heels or something? text: Alright so, few issues with this.Â  Firstly i thought Trailers were ment to put us on the edge of our seats and speak to the child we used to be when we first watched the original picture.Â After watching i felt an intenceÂ "Y U NO DO A MEXICAN PRINCESS YET!?"Â I'm a sucker for the animated movies, hell yes Disney i will throw a wad of cash at you to go see Tangled or PrincessÂ frogÂ anyÂ day of the week, butÂ Â I don't really feelÂ compelled or even interestedÂ in a well crafted shoe..Â  Gravity falls had a better Teaser whenÂ it first came out. I dont think they are trying to replicate frozen i think they are doing what Maleficent is but from the same angle of the original story.Â  I can't help butÂ think it will fall on its face. Maleficent/Sleeping beautyÂ is a story we all knew and loved told from another perspective, were gaining information on this one learning the 'how and why' of one of the most amazing villians ever.Â  With Cinderella its the same story but live action.Â  I can't say that is going to pull the attention of kids, or even muster the attention of an adult considering there have been 8000 remakes already.Â  As i said before, it doesn't seem like there is anything to be gained from this video, I don't feel hungry to watch it as much as other movies. Personally Mulan or Ariel would have been a better choice then watching a girl get her heart broken by abusive siblings before dawning an obnoxiously sky blue get up.Â  But knowing Disney and its many many many spectacular films, anything they set hands to will make an impressive amount of coin. I adore Disney, but there's always that feeling that some things should be left animated.

text: Disney company, please, I understand that the way of the fairy-tale/storyteller is that it is supposed to be passed down from generation to generation with tweeks to reflect what is needed to be taught to, and to better connect to, the listening generation; that's what the Disney Vault is for! But could it be possible to choose to make a rendition of a story or film that NEEDS a rendition. The classic Walt Disney Animated Feature of Cinderella is one of his strongest movies and has aged remarkably well. It's unnecessary, Make a movie rendition of a less Disney movie that had great potential but fell flat do to technical difficulties or being beyond it's time or of a movie with outdated film conventions that wouldn't connect as easily with a casual modern audience. From the late 90's on you've been on this streak of botching an master artist with sequels and live-action reiterations of his work. Your almost as bad as the majority of internet fanfictioneers. No I seen those sequels, those are fan fictions. You're practically hitching a ride on Cinderella's overwhelming success right now.

text: I don't know about you guys, but I like the live action angle Disney is taking with their fairy tales. I mean, yeah, Tangled, Brave, and Frozen are all fantastic, but let's face it; after being bombarded for the past decade with Shrek sequel after Shrek sequel after Shrek sequel, and (in all fairness) the baby boom of Disney princess movies over the last five years, the animated fairytale seems to be somewhat over used, don't you think?  Â  I haven't seen Maleficent yet (obviously) but from what I've seen in the trailers, I'm liking the dark twist Disney is giving their classics as live action films. And if you want to add some darkness, live action is probably the best way to go. (i.e. Once Upon A Time. You think people would've taken that show seriously if it were animated?) I'm sure Maleficent is the first in a long line of Disney live action reboots, which doesn't have to be bad, I mean it is DISNEY after all, and aside from the dark ages, and that insulting Pixar spin off (which, for the love of Hans Christian Andersen, do NOT ask me to name) Disney has never really let us down. Now, I know I can't really judge from this 1 minute fly around of Elsa's...sorry...Cinderella's shoe if it's going to have a dark twist like Maleficent, but if it does, shut up and take my money, Disney! (It may help you to know that I'm a HUGE Disney fan boy...just FYI :3 )  Oh, but Disney is going to ruin Marvel and Lucas Film you say? Well let me ask you this, buddy; Just how badly did the Avengers suck? Hmm? Bottom line, I'm excited for this film, and now you have my reasons why. I'm the Nostal...I mean...Peace!

text: I can't really believe the amount of negative comments posted here.Â  What are you people wasting your time posting here for if you hate Disney and Disney movies?Â  It's my feeling that they retell these stories every so often because the children who enjoyed the previous versions have grown up and have had children of their own.Â  The world changes, and the stories have to be updated so that new generations of children will enjoy the movies instead of watching some 50 year old cartoon.Â  I don't mind the remakes.Â  If I don't wanna see it, I wont, but that's no reason for me to speak negatively about it.  I think this movie might be good.Â  Already the cast gives me reason to hope.Â  it stars Lily Allen and James Madden, stars of the immensely popular Downton Abbey and Game of Thrones, as well as this year's Oscar winner for best actress, Kate Blanchett, and another Oscar winner in Helena Bonham-Carter, though it might simpy be a case of nepotism since her husband Kenneth Branagh is the director.Â  That's the only thing that worries me, because I wasn't a huge fan of his last couple of movies, but maybe he'll get this one right.Â Â  I enjoyed Thor.Â   Have a little hope, people, and just wait and see what happens.Â  I think this will be a great family movie and tell a wonderful story so I'm looking forward to it.Â  Have a nice day everyone, and please, try and be a little kinder towards each other.Â  It's only a movie!!!Â  Feel free to go out and make one so we can critique it if you feel up to it!!Â

text: I don't see what's wrong with all these Disney remakes. I mean, I thought Mirror Mirror was alright (not remade by Disney), but it doesn't have the "Disney magic" a lot of the old films have, same with the Alice in Wonderland remake (not a bad movie, it just didn't draw me into it). I just saw Maleficent the other day and fell in love with it. It truly impressed me. And honestly, there (to me) seems to be a cycle of a remake that is bad or simply decent (usually the first) and then a very good one (in Disney made movies). I think we should give Disney a chance to prove themselves a good movie company once again. They've fallen into a pit, but seem to be getting better. I am looking forward to their future movies. I've been disappointed these past two years, since Brave came out. Now things might be getting better, like Frozen (and I'm not saying Frozen was perfect, it's just much better than what I've been seeing from Disney). Big Hero 6 looks really good to me. Also, to be clear, I personally like this trailer. It intrigues me.

text: I'm not sure if this is mere coincidence. Yet, this year many (thousands) of Americans will get 2 see 2 versions of Cinderella.  I just saw Rogers and Hamerstein's Cinderella a few days ago at the Paramount in Seattle. I do like the idea of adding Jean-Michel who is a student revolutionary who is against the injustice that prince Topher ' s kingdom has been evicting the poor. It adds a little politics to a fairy tale.i also liked that it was a masked ball--very Shakespearean.  And guess what? We have another version coming in a couple weeks: this one. I just thought it odd that the Rogers And Hamerstein version that was on Broadway a couple years ago had the same logo as the Disney one. Though, the broadway one has a little more pink in the background.   I wonder if Disney will add in Jean-Michell. Probably not.   Wouldn't Be weird if Disney and Rogers and Hamerstein both had their versions of Cinderella on Broadway At The Same time? That would be really confusing.  Now it just may be ignorance, but this movie is not Rogers and Hamerstein version with Disney just being the production company?  I don't think it is. But if it was, that would be an awesome marketing strategy.   Has anyone seen the updated Rogers and Hamerstein's version this year? Apparently,  it went through some changes according to the fans.
